The Networking Architecture

1. To give a container its own IP address that can reach the internet, we have to act like virtual electricians. We need three components:

2. The Virtual Switch (Bridge): We will create a virtual network switch on your host machine called appnet.

3. The Virtual Cable (veth pair): A veth (Virtual Ethernet) pair is quite literally a virtual ethernet cable with two ends.

4. The Wiring: We plug one end of the cable into the appnet switch on your host, and we shove the other end inside the container's isolated network namespace.

Once wired, the container sends packets through its end of the cable, they pop out on the host's appnet switch, and the host routes them to the actual internet.


·network.py
Phase 1 (Provisioning): 
	Creates a unique, bi-directional virtual Ethernet cable pair (veth_host and veth_guest) mapped to the container's PID.

Phase 2 (Anchoring): 
	Plugs the veth_host end directly into the host's appnet virtual bridge switch and powers on the interface link.

Phase 3 (Isolation): 
	Transfers the veth_guest end out of the host namespace and pushes it into the container’s isolated network namespace.

Phase 4 (Renaming): 
	Enters the container namespace to activate the local loopback (127.0.0.1) and renames the cryptic guest link to standard eth0.

Phase 5 (Routing): 
	Binds the static IP 10.0.0.2/24 to eth0 and points the container's default gateway route directly back to the host bridge (10.0.0.1).
